  "prompt": "Light needs a medium to travel, so how does sunlight come from space?",
  "response": "Actually, light does not need a medium to travel. Light, which is a form of electromagnetic radiation, can travel through the vacuum of space. The idea that light needs a medium to propagate is a misconception. \n\nElectromagnetic waves, including visible light, travel by oscillating electric and magnetic fields. In a vacuum, these oscillations can propagate without the need for a physical medium. This is how sunlight is able to travel through the vast emptiness of space and reach Earth.\n\nThe concept that light needs a medium to propagate was part of the now outdated \"luminiferous aether\" theory, which was debunked by experiments such as the famous Michelson-Morley experiment in the late 19th century. Modern physics, based on relativity and quantum mechanics, recognizes that electromagnetic radiation can travel through the vacuum of space.",
